The White House held a call with governors to discuss the Administration's response to the situation at the border. They are focused on addressing immediate challenges, ramping up prosecution efforts against smuggling networks, and addressing the root of the problem through diplomatic efforts in Central America. The Administration is working with states and local communities to identify temporary sheltering capacity for unaccompanied minors. Preliminary data show a decrease in daily apprehensions of unaccompanied children by Customs and Border Patrol. The Administration emphasized the importance of Congress fully funding their supplemental request to provide resources for border patrol agents and immigration courts. They also discussed the notification process for governors when unaccompanied minors are placed in their states. The Administration called on Congress to fix the broken immigration system through comprehensive reform.